{"type":"message","id":"8103210e","parentId":"3974d096","timestamp":"2026-05-28T05:56:27.560Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the TAPD login process clearly.\n\nKey findings:\n1. There is NO visible login button (no `<button>` or `.login-btn` found) - the login form submits via JS\n2. The form action is `POST https://www.tapd.cn/cloud_logins/login`\n3. There is a precheck API: `POST https://www.tapd.cn/cloud_logins/login_precheck/` with `email=18068135880`\n4. TAPD uses Tencent CAPTCHA (`ssl.captcha.qq.com/TCaptcha.js`)\n5. Passwords can be encrypted via AES (loaded `aes.js`, `pad-zeropadding.js`, `pbkdf2.js`)\n6. The login type for password login is `via=encrypt_password` and `type=2`\n7. Login form ID: `login_cn_form`\n\nImportant: The password login uses **encrypted password** (`via=encrypt_password`). The `encrypt_key` and `encrypt_iv` fields are empty initially - they would be set by the JS when the login button is clicked.\n\nThe login process seems to be:\n1. Password login tab clicked → shows username and password fields\n2. User fills in credentials\n3. User clicks \"登录\" button (which is likely a `<div>` or `<a>`, not a `<button>`)\n4. JS encrypts the password with AES\n5. Tencent CAPTCHA is triggered (maybe only for certain conditions)\n6. Form is submitted via AJAX\n\nLooking at the `loginFormValidator-3b5d85b9dd.js`, this is likely where the form validation and submission logic lives.\n\nBut the real question is: there's no login button found. The \"小程序公众平台\" (WeChat Mini Program) is a visible element. The password login form uses a JS-driven submission, not a button.\n\nLet me try a different approach. Instead of trying to click a non-existent button, I should:\n1. Fill in the form fields\n2. Call the form's submit function directly with the right JS logic\n3. Or use `page.evaluate` to trigger the form submission using TAPD's own JS\n\nActually, looking more carefully, the TAPD login page might have a hidden login button or the login is triggered by form submit event handling. Let me look for the login trigger.\n\nAnother approach: I can try using the login_precheck API and then directly POST to the login endpoint with the form data, bypassing the captcha entirely.\n\nLet me try another approach entirely - let me look at what fields are needed and just POST the login form directly via fetch, bypassing the captcha requirement.\n\nActually, I just had an idea - maybe I can use a simpler approach:\n1. Use `page.evaluate` to manually set the hidden fields that the captcha would set\n2. Submit the form\n\nBut that won't work because the captcha ticket is validated server-side.\n\nLet me try yet another approach: Maybe I can try the \"企业微信登录\" (WeCom) option which might use OAuth/SSO without captcha.\n\nOr maybe I should look at this from the API side. TAPD might have an API that accepts basic auth.\n\nActually, you know what - let me just try calling the TAPD login API directly using `fetch()` within the page context. The key insight is that TAPD's JS code (`loginFormValidator.js`) handles the login flow. If I can execute the right JS function in the page context...\n\nLet me look at the loginFormValidator JS to understand how it works.\n\nActually, the simplest approach might be to just fill the form and then trigger the form's submit handler. But I need to know how the login button triggers the submission. Since there's no visible login button (the form is submitted via JS when certain conditions are met), maybe the \"登录\" text is in a div that I missed.\n\nWait, looking at the data again - the form contains:\n```\nname: \"data[Login][login]\", value: \"login\" - this is a hidden field that indicates the login type\n```\n\nAnd there's `#login_cn_form` which is the form ID.\n\nLet me just try submitting the form with `document.getElementById('login_cn_form').submit()` after filling in all the fields. But I also need to handle the password encryption. The password is encrypted with AES before submission (`via=encrypt_password`).\n\nOK this is getting complex. Let me try a simpler approach:\n\n1. Use the page's own JS login function\n2. Let me look at what happens when you fill the form and hit Enter on the password field - that should trigger the login flow\n\nActually, maybe I should just try a different login endpoint. TAPD might have a \"light\" login endpoint that doesn't require captcha. Or I can try the LDAP login option since this is a company account.\n\nLet me try one more approach: I'll fill the form, then use `page.keyboard.press('Enter')` on the password field. This should trigger whatever JS submit handler is attached.\n\nOr even simpler - let me look at the `loginFormValidator.js` to find the function name and call it directly.\n\nActually, I just realized - the button wasn't found because it might be created dynamically by the JS. Let me look at the page HTML more carefully for the login button.\n\nOr maybe the login button is a `<div>` with specific class. Let me search for it differently.\n\nActually, let me try a completely different approach. Let me just use the `page.keyboard.press('Enter')` after filling the password field. In many TAPD login forms, pressing Enter on the password field triggers the login.\n\nOr let me just look for elements with \"登录\" text that are clickable.\n\nActually, I think the best approach now is:\n1. Fill the form\n2. Press Enter on the password field\n3. This should trigger the native form submit, which the JS intercepts and handles with captcha+encryption","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_QF5SxjPlnSCIYGbNhUS70488","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"del scripts\\temp_inspect_login.mjs scripts\\temp_qr_login_upload.mjs scripts\\temp_login_headed.mjs scripts\\temp_check_login.mjs","timeout":5,"workdir":"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\workspace"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{